---
import WritingLayout from '../../layouts/WritingLayout.astro';
import { writingPosts } from '../../data/writing';

const post = writingPosts.find(p => p.slug === 'gitops-release-gates')!;
---

<WritingLayout post={post}>
  <h2>Why Release Gates Fail</h2>
  <p>
    Most GitOps release gates fail for one of two reasons: they're too aggressive and generate
    constant noise that engineers learn to ignore, or they're too permissive and don't catch actual
    regressions. Both outcomes destroy trust in the automation.
  </p>
  <p>
    The goal is gates that engineers trust enough to let run unsupervised — and know enough to
    override when they have context the gate doesn't.
  </p>

  <h2>The Stack</h2>
  <p>
    Our setup: FluxCD for GitOps reconciliation, Prometheus for health metrics, and a custom
    gate controller that blocks Flux's <code>Kustomization</code> progression until health checks pass.
  </p>
  <p>
    FluxCD's native <code>HealthChecks</code> field handles basic readiness — pod restarts, deployment
    rollouts. For semantic health (is the service actually working, not just running), we needed
    something on top of it.
  </p>

  <h2>Prometheus Health Checks</h2>
  <p>
    Each service exposes a set of SLI metrics. The release gate queries these via the Prometheus
    HTTP API during a bake window after each deploy. If any SLI degrades beyond a threshold, the
    gate fires.
  </p>
  <p>
    The three checks we run on every deploy:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Error rate delta</strong> — compare p99 error rate in the 10 minutes post-deploy vs the 10-minute baseline before deploy. Alert if delta &gt; 5%.</li>
    <li><strong>Latency shift</strong> — p95 latency before vs after. More sensitive than p99 for catching regressions that haven't yet caused errors.</li>
    <li><strong>Saturation</strong> — CPU and memory vs the service's defined limits. Catches memory leaks and CPU regressions that wouldn't show in error rates immediately.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Thresholds are defined per-service in the GitOps repo. Services with inherently noisy metrics
    get wider bands. New services start with strict defaults and widen as we learn their baseline.
  </p>

  <h2>FluxCD Rollback Behavior</h2>
  <p>
    When a gate fires, FluxCD doesn't automatically roll back. It suspends the <code>Kustomization</code>
    and fires an alert. Engineers decide whether to roll back, hotfix forward, or override the gate.
  </p>
  <p>
    This was a deliberate choice. Automatic rollbacks sound good but create problems:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>During incidents, an auto-rollback can hide the faulty commit in git history in ways that are hard to untangle</li>
    <li>Some regressions are expected and accepted (e.g., a feature that intentionally increases latency for correctness)</li>
    <li>Rollback isn't always safe — database migrations, external API changes, and stateful services can make rollback worse than the regression</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Instead, the gate surfaces all the information and puts the decision with the engineer. The
    override is a single label on the Flux object — auditable, reversible, and clear in the git diff.
  </p>

  <h2>Keeping It Understandable During Incidents</h2>
  <p>
    A gate that fires during a production incident adds cognitive load at the worst time. Two things
    that helped:
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Gate output links to the dashboard.</strong> When the Prometheus check fails, the alert
    message includes a pre-built Grafana URL scoped to that service, that deploy's time window, and
    the specific metric that tripped the gate. Engineers land directly on the relevant graph, not
    the Grafana home screen.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Gates have named reasons.</strong> "Health gate failed" is useless. "Error rate gate:
    observed 8.2%, threshold 5%, baseline 1.1%" is actionable. The gate controller formats its
    status condition with the exact numbers that triggered it.
  </p>

  <h2>What We Got Wrong Initially</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Querying Prometheus at exactly T+0 post-deploy. Metrics take 15-30 seconds to scrape. We were comparing stale pre-deploy data to itself and calling it a pass. Added a 60s startup delay to all bake windows.</li>
    <li>Using the same thresholds for all environments. Staging traffic is synthetic and behaves differently than production. Separate threshold configs per environment are necessary, not optional.</li>
    <li>Not accounting for time-of-day variance. A 5% error rate increase at 3am during low traffic looks like noise. The same increase at peak is critical. We moved to relative thresholds (% change from rolling baseline) instead of absolute values.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Trust Problem Is the Hard Part</h2>
  <p>
    Technical correctness isn't enough. Engineers need to understand why a gate fired, be able to
    investigate it quickly, and trust that overriding it is safe and auditable. If any of those
    properties are missing, they'll start bypassing the gate by default — and you're back to
    manual deploys with extra steps.
  </p>
  <p>
    The investment in clear error messages, dashboard links, and a well-documented override process
    paid for itself in the first quarter. Fewer bypasses, faster incident response, and engineering
    trust in the automation that's supposed to protect them.
  </p>
</WritingLayout>
